<div class="content">
  <p>
    Ember uses its routing system as a stack. The browser history itself stores
    the stack and we can push and pop from this stack with
    <code>\{{link-to}}</code> and <code>window.history.back()</code>
    respectively.
  </p>

  <p>Given the following routes in Ember:</p>

{{#code-highlight lang="js"}}
Router.map(function() {
  this.route('stack-navigation', function () {
    this.route('stack1');
    this.route('stack2');
    this.route('stack3');
  });
});
{{/code-highlight}}

  <p>Then your <code>stack-navigation.hbs</code> might look like:</p>

{{#code-highlight lang="handlebars"}}
\{{#ons-page}}
  \{{#ons-toolbar}}
    &lt;div class="left"&gt;
      \{{ons-back-button events=(hash click=(action "goBack"))}}
    &lt;/div&gt;

    &lt;div class="center"&gt;
      Navigation Stack Title
    &lt;/div&gt;
  \{{/ons-toolbar}}

  \{{outlet}}

\{{/ons-page}}
{{/code-highlight}}

  <p style="text-align: center">
    {{#link-to "stack-navigation.stack2" tagName="ons-button"}}
      Read about pushing and popping from the stack
    {{/link-to}}
  </p>
</div>
